### Featured article

[An Experiment on a Bird in the Air Pump](/An_Experiment_on_a_Bird_in_the_Air_Pump) is a 1768 [oil-on-canvas painting](/Oil_painting) by [Joseph Wright of Derby](/Joseph_Wright_of_Derby), a true master of capturing the peculiar glow of scientific inquiry. This particular masterpiece forms part of a series of candlelit scenes that Wright, with his characteristic flair for dramatic illumination, meticulously painted during the 1760s. What makes *The Air Pump* truly remarkable is its audacious departure from the prevailing artistic conventions of the era; it dared to depict a scientific subject, a mere experiment, with the same reverence and gravitas formerly reserved solely for scenes of profound historical or religious significance. Wright, it seems, was intimately involved in chronicling the dawn of the [Industrial Revolution](/Industrial_Revolution) and the intellectual ferment of the [Enlightenment](/Age_of_Enlightenment), capturing these seismic shifts with an almost unsettling clarity. While his contemporaries certainly recognized his paintings as something truly extraordinary and out of the ordinary, his provincial status and his rather unconventional choice of subjects meant that his distinctive style, regrettably, never achieved widespread imitation. Today, this captivating picture has been a cherished possession of the [National Gallery](/National_Gallery,_London) since 1863, and it continues to be rightly regarded as an enduring masterpiece of British art, a testament to its enduring power. The painting itself offers a glimpse into a bygone era of scientific exploration, depicting a [natural philosopher](/Natural_philosophy) – the intellectual precursor to our modern scientist – as he meticulously recreates one of [Robert Boyle](/Robert_Boyle)'s seminal [air pump](/Vacuum_pump) experiments. The central, rather unsettling premise involves a bird being slowly, deliberately deprived of oxygen, all before a varied and rather curious group of onlookers. This assembled audience displays a fascinating spectrum of human reactions, though for most, the insatiable pull of scientific curiosity appears to triumph over any immediate concern for the poor avian subject. The central figure, with an almost theatrical flourish, looks directly out of the picture, effectively inviting the viewer's complicity and participation in the unfolding, dramatic outcome. ( [Full article...](/An_Experiment_on_a_Bird_in_the_Air_Pump) )

