### Featured biography

[W. S. Gilbert](/W._S._Gilbert), an [English](/United_Kingdom) [dramatist](/Dramatist), [librettist](/Libretto), and rather talented illustrator, is primarily, and perhaps eternally, known for his prolific output of fourteen [comic operas](/Comic_opera). These works, which have graced stages for generations, were produced in a famously successful, if sometimes tumultuous, [collaboration](/Gilbert_and_Sullivan) with the esteemed [composer](/Composer) [Sir Arthur Sullivan](/Arthur_Sullivan). Among Gilbert's most enduring and popular collaborations with Sullivan are theatrical staples such as [H.M.S. Pinafore](/H.M.S._Pinafore), [The Pirates of Penzance](/The_Pirates_of_Penzance), and, of course, [The Mikado](/The_Mikado), which still reigns as one of the most frequently performed works in the entire history of musical theatre. Indeed, most of their other [Savoy operas](/Savoy_opera) continue to be performed with remarkable regularity today, not just throughout the English-speaking world but far beyond, by professional opera companies, dedicated [repertory](/Repertory) companies, enthusiastic schools, and countless community theatre groups. The linguistic legacy of Gilbert's wit is undeniable, with lines from these works having permanently permeated the English language, becoming common parlance. Phrases such as "short, sharp shock" (a rather apt description for some of life's unpleasant surprises), "What never? Well, hardly ever!", and the rather legalistic yet satisfying "let the punishment fit the crime" are all his enduring contributions. Beyond his operatic triumphs, Gilbert also penned the delightful [Bab Ballads](/Bab_Ballads), an extensive and much-loved collection of light verse, charmingly accompanied by his own distinctive and comical drawings. His creative output was truly prodigious, encompassing over 75 plays and libretti, a myriad of stories, poems, lyrics, and various other comic and serious pieces. His innovative plays and his pioneering, [realistic](/Realism_(arts)) style of stage direction proved to be a significant source of inspiration for subsequent generations of dramatists, including literary giants like [Oscar Wilde](/Oscar_Wilde) and [George Bernard Shaw](/George_Bernard_Shaw), solidifying his place not just in musical theatre, but in the broader tapestry of English drama. ( [Full article...](/W._S._Gilbert) )

