Image 4

[Caterpillar](/Caterpillar_(Alice%27s_Adventures_in_Wonderland)), Alice's Adventures in Wonderland
Artist: Sir [John Tenniel](/John_Tenniel)

Sir [John Tenniel](/John_Tenniel)'s iconic illustration of the enigmatic [Caterpillar](/Caterpillar_(Alice%27s_Adventures_in_Wonderland)) for [Lewis Carroll](/Lewis_Carroll)'s timeless classic, *[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland](/Alice%27s_Adventures_in_Wonderland)*. This particular illustration is widely noted for its rather ambiguous central figure, which possesses the remarkable quality of being viewed either as having a distinctly human male's face, complete with a pointed nose and a somewhat protruding lower lip, or, if one prefers, as the actual head end of a [caterpillar](/Caterpillar), with its three "true" legs subtly visible on the right. The small, almost imperceptible symbol in the lower left corner is composed of Tenniel's initials, his customary signature for most of his meticulous work for the book. The partially obscured word in the lower left-center, a detail often missed, is the last name of Edward Dalziel, the skilled [engraver](/Engraving) responsible for bringing Tenniel's vision to life on the page.

[More featured pictures](/Portal:United_Kingdom/Featured_picture)

