Image 5

[Gilbert and Sullivan](/Gilbert_and_Sullivan)
Image credit: [Alfred Bryan](/Alfred_Bryan_(Illustrator))

The legendary duo of [Gilbert and Sullivan](/Gilbert_and_Sullivan) gifted the world fourteen [comic operas](/Comic_opera), a collection that includes such enduring masterpieces as [H.M.S. Pinafore](/H.M.S._Pinafore), [The Pirates of Penzance](/The_Pirates_of_Penzance), and the eternally popular [The Mikado](/The_Mikado). Many of these works, despite the passage of time, are still performed with remarkable frequency today, a testament to their enduring appeal. However, the events surrounding their 1889 collaboration, *[The Gondoliers](/The_Gondoliers)*, led to a rather spectacular argument and a subsequent [lawsuit](/Lawsuit) that effectively, and rather dramatically, divided the two creative partners. It wasn't until 1891, after numerous failed attempts at reconciliation by both Gilbert and Sullivan themselves, and their ever-patient producer, [Richard D'Oyly Carte](/Richard_D%27Oyly_Carte), that Tom Chappell, Gilbert and Sullivan's music publisher, wisely stepped in to mediate between two of his most profitable, and most stubborn, artists. In a surprisingly swift turn of events, he succeeded within a mere two weeks. This charming cartoon, published in *The Entr'acte*, perfectly captures the magazine's palpable pleasure at the much-anticipated reuniting of D'Oyly Carte (depicted on the left), Gilbert (centre), and Sullivan (on the right). A happy ending, at least for a while.

[More featured pictures](/Portal:United_Kingdom/Featured_picture)

