Image 7

[Roman Baths](/Roman_Baths_(Bath))
Photograph credit: [David Iliff](/User:Diliff)

The [Roman Baths](/Roman_Baths_(Bath)) complex represents a site of immense historical interest, nestled within the charming English city of [Bath, Somerset](/Bath,_Somerset). This remarkably well-preserved site, dating back to the era of [Roman Britain](/Roman_Britain), once served as a bustling hub for [public bathing]—a rather essential social ritual in Roman times. The ancient [Roman baths](/Thermae) themselves are situated beneath the modern street level, a testament to layers of history. The complex is comprised of four primary features: the sacred spring, the Roman temple, the Roman bath house, and the accompanying museum, which proudly houses numerous [finds](/Artifact_(archaeology)) unearthed from [the Roman town](/Aquae_Sulis) of Aquae Sulis. The architectural structures visible above street level, often mistaken for Roman, actually date from the 19th century. The Baths remain a major tourist attraction, and, in conjunction with the adjacent [Grand Pump Room](/Grand_Pump_Room), welcomed over 1.3 million visitors in 2018. While visitors are permitted to tour the baths and museum, the ancient waters themselves are, quite understandably, off-limits for a dip. This particular picture showcases the grand Great Bath of the Roman Baths complex, with the imposing [Bath Abbey](/Bath_Abbey) majestically visible in the background. It's worth noting that the entire structure rising above the level of the pillar bases is, in fact, a later construction, adding another layer to its complex history.

[More featured pictures](/Portal:United_Kingdom/Featured_picture)

