Image 8

[British First World War recruitment poster](/History_of_the_United_Kingdom_during_World_War_I)
Poster: Parliamentary Recruiting Committee; restoration: [Adam Cuerden](/User:Adam_Cuerden)

A rather striking British recruitment poster from the tumultuous period of the First World War, featuring the timeless and evocative imagery of [Saint George and the Dragon](/Saint_George_and_the_Dragon). During [Britain's involvement in the First World War](/History_of_the_United_Kingdom_during_the_First_World_War), the nation managed to field a formidable force of more than five million troops, a staggering number. [Enrollment](/Recruitment_to_the_British_Army_during_the_First_World_War) into the armed forces was initially voluntary, and throughout 1914 and 1915, the British military assiduously released numerous such recruitment posters, each designed to appeal to patriotic duty and attract willing troops. However, as the brutal conflict dragged on, the number of [volunteers dwindled](/Monthly_recruiting_figures_for_the_British_Army_in_the_First_World_War), a predictable consequence of the grim realities of trench warfare. By 1916, necessity dictated the introduction of the [Military Service Act](/Military_Service_Act_1916), which formally provided for the [conscription](/Conscription) of single men aged 18 to 41. By the war's bitter end, the scope of this law had been further extended, encompassing both older and married men, a testament to the insatiable demand for manpower.

[More featured pictures](/Portal:United_Kingdom/Featured_picture)

