Image 11

[Ophelia (painting)](/Ophelia_(painting))
Painting: [John Everett Millais](/John_Everett_Millais)

*[Ophelia](/Ophelia_(painting))* is an exquisite [oil painting](/Oil_painting) on canvas, meticulously completed by Sir [John Everett Millais](/John_Everett_Millais) between 1851 and 1852. This iconic work vividly depicts the tragic character of [Ophelia](/Ophelia), drawn from [Shakespeare](/William_Shakespeare)'s timeless and often unsettling play, *[Hamlet](/Hamlet)*. The painting captures her in the poignant act of singing, just moments before she succumbs to drowning in a river in [Denmark]. This specific, heart-wrenching death scene is, notably, not actually witnessed onstage within the play itself, but is instead eloquently described in a powerful speech delivered by [Queen Gertrude](/Gertrude_(Hamlet)). The painting's creation was a two-stage process: first, the remarkably detailed natural setting was painstakingly rendered, drawn directly from the serene [Hogsmill River](/Hogsmill_River) in [Surrey]; subsequently, Ophelia herself was added, portrayed by the muse and artist's model, [Elizabeth Siddal]. Today, this invaluable painting is proudly owned by [Tate Britain] and is currently valued at an astonishing figure exceeding £30 million, a testament to its artistic and cultural significance.

[More featured pictures](/Portal:United_Kingdom/Featured_picture)

