[Charles I of England](/Charles_I_of_England)
Painting: [Anthony van Dyck](/Anthony_van_Dyck)

[Charles I](/Charles_I_of_England) (19 November 1600 – 30 January 1649) served as monarch over the three distinct kingdoms of [England](/Kingdom_of_England), [Scotland](/Kingdom_of_Scotland), and [Ireland](/Kingdom_of_Ireland), a reign that commenced in 1625 and concluded rather abruptly with his execution in 1649. As the second son of [King James VI of Scotland](/King_James_VI_of_Scotland) (who also became James I of England), he spent the vast majority of his life in England after his father inherited the English throne in 1603. His reign became notoriously marked by escalating quarrels and persistent clashes with the [Parliament of England](/Parliament_of_England), an institution that increasingly sought to curb his perceived [royal prerogative](/Royal_prerogative). From 1642 onwards, Charles found himself locked in a bitter and protracted struggle, battling the armies of both the English and Scottish parliaments in what became known as the devastating [English Civil War](/English_Civil_War). His eventual defeat led directly to his unprecedented execution, an act that sent shockwaves across Europe and was followed by the establishment of a short-lived republic, known as the [Commonwealth of England](/Commonwealth_of_England). This particular painting, majestically titled *[Equestrian Portrait of Charles I](/Equestrian_Portrait_of_Charles_I)*, is an [oil-on-canvas work](/Oil_painting) by Charles's esteemed [Principal Painter in Ordinary](/Principal_Painter_in_Ordinary), [Anthony van Dyck](/Anthony_van_Dyck). The portrait, now a prized possession in the [National Gallery] in London, is generally believed to have been painted around 1637–38, and stands as one of many iconic portraits of Charles created by van Dyck, including several other notable [equestrian portraits](/Equestrian_portrait).

