Image 13

[George IV](/George_IV)
Artist: [Sir Thomas Lawrence](/Thomas_Lawrence_(painter))

An exquisite [oil on canvas](/Oil_on_canvas) portrait of [George IV of the United Kingdom](/George_IV) in his capacity as the [Prince Regent], meticulously captured by the celebrated artist [Sir Thomas Lawrence](/Thomas_Lawrence_(painter)). In the year 1814, [Lord Stewart](/Charles_Vane,_3rd_Marquess_of_Londonderry), who had recently been appointed ambassador in Vienna and was, conveniently, a previous patron of Thomas Lawrence, expressed a keen desire to commission a portrait of the Prince Regent from the artist. To facilitate this, he arranged for Lawrence to be formally presented to the Prince Regent at a [levée]. Soon after this auspicious introduction, the Prince himself paid a visit to Lawrence at his studio in [Russell Square]. Lawrence, clearly thrilled by the royal attention, wrote to his brother, recounting the event with palpable excitement: "To crown this honour, [he] engag'd to sit to me at one today and after a successful sitting of two hours, has just left me and comes again tomorrow and the next day." A rather busy schedule for a future king, one might observe.

