Image 15

[Edward VI of England](/Edward_VI_of_England)
Artist: Unknown, probably of the [Flemish School](/Flemish_School)

A captivating portrait of [Edward VI of England](/Edward_VI_of_England), captured during his youth when he held the esteemed title of [Prince of Wales]. He is depicted prominently wearing a distinctive [badge](/Heraldic_badge) adorned with the iconic [Prince of Wales's feathers]. This painting was most likely executed in 1546, when Edward was merely eight years old, during his residence at [Hunsdon House]. The following year, Edward ascended to the throne, becoming [King of England], [King of France], and Edward I of [Ireland]. He holds the significant historical position as the third monarch of the powerful [Tudor dynasty] and, notably, England's very first ruler who was openly [Protestant] at the precise moment of his ascension to the throne. Edward's entire, albeit brief, rule was conducted and mediated through a council of [regency]. He tragically died at the tender age of 15 in 1553, leaving behind a legacy of what might have been.

