### In the news

Here's a snapshot of recent events, proving that the world, and particularly the UK, never truly stands still.

15 November 2025 – [Modern immigration to the United Kingdom](/Modern_immigration_to_the_United_Kingdom)
[British](/United_Kingdom) [home secretary](/Home_secretary) [Shabana Mahmood](/Shabana_Mahmood) has officially announced comprehensive plans to significantly reduce the length of time individuals can hold [refugee status], to extend the required period before applying for [long-term residency], and to terminate automatic [state benefits](/Welfare_state_in_the_United_Kingdom) for asylum seekers. These measures form a rather sweeping reform of the country's asylum system, a policy shift that is unlikely to be met with universal acclaim. (AFP via CBS News)

14 November 2025 – [Mariana dam disaster](/Mariana_dam_disaster)
In a significant legal development, [British](/United_Kingdom) [High Court judge](/High_Court_judge_(England_and_Wales)) [Finola O'Farrell](/Finola_O%27Farrell) has ruled that the [Australian](/Australia) mining corporation [BHP](/BHP) is indeed liable for the catastrophic 2015 [Samarco](/Samarco) dam collapse in [Mariana](/Mariana,_Minas_Gerais), [Minas Gerais](/Minas_Gerais), [Brazil](/Brazil). This tragic event is widely considered to be the largest environmental disaster ever to strike the country, a ruling that will undoubtedly have far-reaching implications. ( *The Guardian* ) (G1)

13 November 2025 – [Syria–United Kingdom relations](/Syria%E2%80%93United_Kingdom_relations)
The [Syrian](/Syria) [foreign minister](/Ministry_of_Foreign_Affairs_(Syria)) has presided over the reopening of the country's [embassy] in [London](/London), [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom). This diplomatic re-establishment comes after the embassy's closure in 2013, a direct consequence of the onset of the brutal [Syrian civil war]. A gesture of thawing relations, perhaps, or simply a pragmatic necessity. (AP)

11 November 2025 –
The [Southwark Crown Court](/Southwark_Crown_Court) in [London](/London), [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom), has handed down a significant sentence: [Chinese](/Chinese_people) [fraudster](/Fraud) [Qian Zhimin](/Qian_Zhimin_(criminal)) received 11 years and eight months in [prison](/Prisons_in_the_United_Kingdom) for orchestrating a massive [Ponzi scheme]. This elaborate fraud ultimately [defrauded](/Cryptocurrency_and_crime) over 128,000 investors and involved the sophisticated [laundering](/Money_laundering) of proceeds into [Bitcoin]. The case notably resulted in the recovery of approximately ₿61,000, marking it as the country's largest single [cryptocurrency](/Cryptocurrency) seizure to date. (AP)

9 November 2025 – [Belgium–United Kingdom relations](/Belgium%E2%80%93United_Kingdom_relations)
The [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom) has officially announced its decision to deploy its [military](/British_Armed_Forces) personnel to [Belgium](/Belgium), a measure intended to bolster the protection of Belgian airports. This deployment comes amid a series of rather concerning drone incursions observed over the country's [airspace]. A rather modern problem requiring, it seems, a rather traditional solution. (BBC News)

7 November 2025 – [Indonesia–United Kingdom relations](/Indonesia%E2%80%93United_Kingdom_relations), [Capital punishment in Indonesia](/Capital_punishment_in_Indonesia)
[Indonesia](/Indonesia) has confirmed the repatriation of two [British](/British_people) nationals: [Lindsay Sandiford](/Lindsay_Sandiford), who had been sentenced to death for [smuggling](/Drug_trafficking_in_Indonesia) [cocaine](/Cocaine) into [Bali] in 2013, and Shahab Shahabadi, who was serving a [life sentence](/Life_imprisonment) for drug offences. This compassionate decision follows a bilateral agreement made on humanitarian grounds, allowing both individuals to be transferred to the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom) to serve the remainder of their sentences under the jurisdiction of [UK law]. A rare moment of international cooperation, perhaps. (Reuters)

